<section class="faq-section">
<div class="faq-inner">
<h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is Engage? <span class="faq-icon">+</span></div>
<div class="faq-a">Engage is a modern factor-based job evaluation methodology and tool used to determine the relative size of roles in an organisation in a structured, transparent, and defensible way. It focuses on the output and demands of the role rather than the person in the role.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is job evaluation? <span class="faq-icon">+</span></div>
<div class="faq-a">Job evaluation is the process of determining the relative worth of one job compared with another inside an organisation by applying a consistent set of factors or criteria. The outcome is usually a grade, which then supports role hierarchy, benchmarking, and pay structure design.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Why do organisations use job evaluation? <span class="faq-icon">+</span></div>
<div class="faq-a">Organisations use job evaluation to create a common language for role size, analyse role and pay relativities, benchmark externally, support fair pay structures, define progression, and improve consistency in role decisions.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What makes Engage different from traditional job evaluation approaches? <span class="faq-icon">+</span></div>
<div class="faq-a">Traditional approaches often rely heavily on job descriptions, indirect information, specialist evaluators, and processes that can become slow, bureaucratic, and hard to maintain. Engage is designed to be faster, more transparent, more inclusive, and easier to sustain internally. It can be used without full job descriptions and allows direct role knowledge into the process.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Do we need job descriptions to use Engage? <span class="faq-icon">+</span></div>
<div class="faq-a">No. Job descriptions can be useful as a reference point, but they are not required. Engage works best when knowledgeable people participate in the evaluation and provide direct understanding of the role. Role descriptions are useful but not critical.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What does “the role, not the person” mean? <span class="faq-icon">+</span></div>
<div class="faq-a">It means the role is evaluated based on what the organisation requires the job to do, not based on the current employee’s performance, personality, capability, tenure, or future potential. Performance and personal capability are separate issues and should not influence role size.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What does job evaluation not take into account? <span class="faq-icon">+</span></div>
<div class="faq-a">Job evaluation does not consider attitude, personal attributes, performance, future-state ambition, or proficiency of the current incumbent. It also does not by itself determine what an individual should be paid.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What are the five Engage grids? <span class="faq-icon">+</span></div>
<div class="faq-a">The core Engage dimensions are Technical, Managerial, Persuasive, Control, and Impact. These are used together to determine the relative size of the role. Influence can also be used as an alternate grid for certain flexible or person-related assignments.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What does the Technical grid assess? <span class="faq-icon">+</span></div>
<div class="faq-a">The Technical grid looks at the knowledge required by the role and how that knowledge is applied. It assesses the depth, breadth, and integration of knowledge needed to perform the role effectively. It is about role design, not the personal qualifications of the current incumbent alone.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What does the Managerial grid assess? <span class="faq-icon">+</span></div>
<div class="faq-a">The Managerial grid looks at managerial complexity, especially coordination and business decision-making. It focuses on management in the role, not just supervision labels, and is concerned with decisions the role is actually permitted to make.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What does the Persuasive grid assess? <span class="faq-icon">+</span></div>
<div class="faq-a">The Persuasive grid looks at how the role influences others. It includes general communication, collaborative selling, and individual selling depending on the nature of the role. For sales roles, upper parts of the grid are relevant; for most other roles, general communication is more relevant.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What does the Control grid assess? <span class="faq-icon">+</span></div>
<div class="faq-a">The Control grid looks at staff reporting, sites controlled, and related organisational control. It includes direct and indirect employees, but excludes dotted-line relationships. It focuses on the actual scope of organisational control in the role.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What does the Impact grid assess? <span class="faq-icon">+</span></div>
<div class="faq-a">The Impact grid considers the importance and context of the role to the business, including the level of responsibility and reporting level. It looks at how the role affects the organisation’s operations, development, or strategic direction.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">When is the Influence grid used? <span class="faq-icon">+</span></div>
<div class="faq-a">Influence is used as an alternate grid to Impact for more flexible roles and largely person-related assignments, particularly where projection and leadership influence are more central than standard structural impact.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How long does it take to evaluate a role in Engage? <span class="faq-icon">+</span></div>
<div class="faq-a">Engage is designed to be fast and easy to use, with “5 judgments, 5 minutes” as a working principle. In practice, the exact time depends on the quality of role knowledge in the room and the complexity of the role, but the method is intended to be significantly quicker than many traditional approaches.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What does “seek the limit” mean? <span class="faq-icon">+</span></div>
<div class="faq-a">It means evaluators should look for the highest reasonable box or level that the role can genuinely justify, rather than marking conservatively by default. It is often easier to agree on what the role is not than what it is.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Is Engage a scoring system? <span class="faq-icon">+</span></div>
<div class="faq-a">Engage uses factor-based structured judgment and algorithmic conversion, but it is not intended to feel like a mysterious black-box score. The process is designed to be transparent, with visible reasoning behind the judgments and their eventual conversion into grades.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How do the grid results become a grade? <span class="faq-icon">+</span></div>
<div class="faq-a">Each role is evaluated across the relevant grids. The combination of references, together with weightings, is processed through an algorithm that converts the overall output into a grade. That grade can then be aligned to internal or external grading systems such as IPE, Hay, Patterson, TASK, or client-specific systems.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can Engage work with our current grading platform? <span class="faq-icon">+</span></div>
<div class="faq-a">Yes. Results can be provided in the client’s grading platform of choice, including current in-house systems and global systems.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Who should be involved in evaluating roles? <span class="faq-icon">+</span></div>
<div class="faq-a">Ideally, a trained evaluation committee with Human Capital and representative business members should be involved. Engage works best when people with direct knowledge of the work participate, rather than relying only on indirect job documentation.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Why is direct role knowledge so important? <span class="faq-icon">+</span></div>
<div class="faq-a">Traditional methods often exclude first-hand understanding and rely too heavily on position descriptions written by others. Engage is designed to include direct role knowledge because this improves accuracy, credibility, and trust in outcomes.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Do incumbents participate in the process? <span class="faq-icon">+</span></div>
<div class="faq-a">They can. One implementation approach involves multiple people performing the job, which increases buy-in and inclusiveness. Another uses a representative central committee, which can be faster but may reduce direct buy-in.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is the role of the executive session? <span class="faq-icon">+</span></div>
<div class="faq-a">The executive session introduces executives to Engage, explains how role evaluation supports fair pay, agrees terms and definitions, discusses how executives can support the process, and often evaluates and sense-checks executive roles.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Why are briefing sessions important? <span class="faq-icon">+</span></div>
<div class="faq-a">Briefing sessions help inform employees who may not be directly involved in evaluation sessions. They create awareness, answer questions, support transparency, and improve confidence in the process.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is a sense check session? <span class="faq-icon">+</span></div>
<div class="faq-a">A sense check session compares roles against each other by grid references and grade, reviews changes, tests whether the outcomes make sense across the structure, and allows revisions where needed. It is a key quality-control step in the process.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is a loop back session? <span class="faq-icon">+</span></div>
<div class="faq-a">A loop back session is used to communicate sense-check changes back to affected attendees and to allow them to challenge or comment on revised outcomes. It supports an open, dialogue-based process and helps improve transparency and buy-in.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How is job evaluation linked to pay? <span class="faq-icon">+</span></div>
<div class="faq-a">Job evaluation supports pay by creating job grades, which enable market benchmarking and the design of fair pay structures. It helps determine the position component of pay, but pay decisions should also consider the person and performance.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Does a higher grade automatically mean a person should be paid more? <span class="faq-icon">+</span></div>
<div class="faq-a">Not automatically. A higher grade indicates a larger role, which usually influences the reference salary and pay range, but actual pay decisions also consider market position, person factors, and performance. Grading alone does not dictate what individuals should be paid.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What happens after roles are graded? <span class="faq-icon">+</span></div>
<div class="faq-a">After grading, organisations typically move into implementation activities such as title alignment, grade movement analysis, communication, line manager upskilling, appeals handling, and job evaluation policy development. Implementation support and policy are important value-adds.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Why does transparency matter so much in Engage? <span class="faq-icon">+</span></div>
<div class="faq-a">Transparency matters because people tend to criticise what they do not understand, and because grading is often a sensitive part of change. This is not intended to be a black box. Transparency builds trust, reduces suspicion, and strengthens the process overall.</div>
</div>
</div>
</section>

